{
  "id": "019d3c62-7347-7620-b2c0-3123ce6527dc",
  "content": "# Design: Codebase-to-Course Self-Onboarding Engine\n\n## Problem\n\nWhen a repo is onboarded mid-life via `corvia workspace ingest`, corvia gets code chunks and structural edges but no high-level understanding. It cannot answer \"what is this repo about?\" or \"how does the auth subsystem work?\" without pre-existing knowledge entries. This is the cold-start problem for every repo that adopts corvia after initial development.\n\n## Proposed Solution: `corvia workspace synthesize`\n\nA post-ingest LLM synthesis pass that walks the code graph and generates architectural understanding entries. This reframes P6 (LLM-assisted architectural summaries) as a self-onboarding engine that works in concert with the P1-P5 structural intelligence pipeline.\n\n### How it works\n\n**Phase 1: Graph Analysis**\n- Import petgraph `toposort` and `connected_components` (both available, neither imported today)\n- Identify entry points via zero-in-degree nodes on \"imports\" relation\n- Identify leaf modules via zero-out-degree nodes\n- Group chunks by directory (v1) or connected_components/Leiden clustering (v2)\n- Output: ordered list of module groups in topological (dependency) order\n\n**Phase 2: LLM Synthesis (bottom-up, following topological order)**\n- For each module group, starting from leaves:\n  - Gather all chunks in group + structural edges\n  - Call GenerationEngine with structured prompt asking for: purpose, key APIs, dependencies, patterns\n  - Write result as KnowledgeEntry with content_role=\"finding\"\n- For repo-level summary:\n  - Gather all module summaries (just generated)\n  - Synthesize overall architecture description\n- Wire \"summarizes\" edges from summaries to their source chunks\n\n**Phase 3: Relationship Synthesis**\n- For each module pair with cross-edges, synthesize how they relate\n- Wire \"relates_to\" edges between module summaries\n\n### Why bottom-up matters\nSynthesizing leaf modules first means higher-level summaries can reference those descriptions. Corvia builds understanding incrementally, exactly like a course. The topological order from the code graph determines the \"curriculum.\"\n\n## Connection to Structural Intelligence (GitNexus Decision)\n\nP1-P5 structural edges directly feed this feature:\n- P1-P2 (inheritance/calls): More edges = better module grouping, richer synthesis\n- P3 (target resolution): Fewer broken edges = fewer gaps in module graph\n- P4 (edge weight scoring): Prioritize which relationships to highlight in summaries\n- P5 (HashMap optimization): Performance for large repos\n- Phase 2 Leiden clustering (future): Upgrades directory-based grouping to real functional subsystem detection\n\nWithout structural intelligence, grouping is directory-only. With it, corvia can detect cross-directory subsystems via call/import graph connectivity.\n\n## What Already Exists (Reuse)\n\n- GenerationEngine (gRPC + Ollama) for LLM calls\n- QueryableStore for writing entries\n- GraphStore with petgraph DiGraph in memory\n- BFS traversal, A* shortest path, Kosaraju SCC\n- wire_pipeline_relations() for edge creation\n- RAG pipeline augmenter for context assembly\n- content_role=\"finding\" (defined but never auto-assigned during ingest)\n\n## What's New\n\n- petgraph toposort + connected_components imports (~10 lines)\n- Entry point detection function (zero-in-degree query)\n- Directory-based module grouping\n- Synthesis prompt templates\n- Orchestrator loop (graph analysis + prompt + write)\n- CLI: `corvia workspace synthesize [--scope] [--dry-run] [--no-relations]`\n- MCP tool: `corvia_synthesize`\n- Incremental mode: re-synthesize only modules with changed chunks since last run\n\n## Key Design Decisions Pending\n\n1. Module detection strategy for v1 (pure directory vs. connected components)\n2. Token budget per synthesis call (how many chunks to include)\n3. Incremental policy (timestamp-based? hash-based?)\n4. Whether synthesized entries should have a distinct content_role or reuse \"finding\"\n5. Cost guardrails (max LLM calls per ingest, opt-in flag)",
